Perspectives for Sino-American Relations 2019
NEW YORK – In 2018, the new and increasingly unpredictable dynamics of Sino-American relations unsettled large parts of Asia.
Last year, US President Donald Trump returned from his particularly pompous "state visit plus" in Beijing, from which China had hoped that Trump's anti-Chinese election campaign rhetoric would finally belong to the past.
Twelve months later, China and the United States are embroiled in a trade war, and the Trump government has replaced the "strategic engagement" of the USA in China with "strategic competition".
In addition, the US-American, European and Chinese economies and markets were booming a year ago.
There is great uncertainty on the financial markets today, with growth slowing in China and Europe, and higher interest rates beginning to take effect in America.
The uncertainty about the future development of the nuclear negotiations with North Korea is also clouding the picture.
What are the prospects, therefore, for the relations between the US and China in 2019?
It is likely that an agreement will be reached by March on the reduction of the bilateral trade deficit and on the import decisions that China will take in this regard.
An agreement on tariff reductions is also possible by then, although the complexity of the issue could extend the intended timeframe.
One customs duty after another being negotiated could take a year.
However, if Chinese economic reformers were to choose a more drastic approach, by committing themselves to abolishing all customs duties over time and urging the Americans to do the same, a more rapid result could be obtained.
This would, however, go against the interests of Chinese trade officials, who for decades have been trained to be stingy and would hardly give anything up, let alone everything at once.
The reform of the so-called forced technology transfer should be relatively uncomplicated.
Notwithstanding, a reform is something other than the way contractual agreements could be interpreted in practice, even if there were no specific provisions on technology transfer.
Intellectual property protection is, however, extremely problematic.
Earlier agreements made under the government of President Barack Obama could be reaffirmed.
However, enforcement or judicial action for infringements on intellectual property rights remains a futile endeavor.
A possible mechanism could involve subjecting relevant contracts between Chinese and foreign companies to international arbitration tribunals seated in Singapore or Switzerland, which are specifically tasked with enforcing intellectual property protection.
Should China raise objections, it could develop its own international arbitration procedure seated in China.
To strengthen its international credibility, it should appoint qualified foreigners to its arbitration panel, however.
No one trusts Chinese trade courts.
For its own internal need for reform, China needs to move towards entirely independent trade and civil chambers in its judicial system, even if the criminal chamber remains under political control.
The American concerns regarding state subsidies within the framework of China's "Made in China 2025" strategy will hardly be resolved.
In fact, all countries give their domestic technology sectors a degree of state support, although this is highest in China.
Even if we were to prescribe a maximum level of state support for a specific company, compliance would be hard to assess.
I am not optimistic that there will be a negotiation result in this area.
Perhaps America just needs to knock China out of the race by increasing public investments in research and development in the fields of information technology and biotechnology.
We should also not rule out the possibility that China will offer customs reforms to the rest of the international community.
In time, China could decide to take the drastic step of not only agreeing on tariff-free trade with the US, but with all members of the World Trade Organization.
China would thereby have a nearly irresistible opportunity to position itself as a champion of global free trade and to stem the tide of protectionism.
In the course of such a turn, China could ask the member states of the Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP) to join, in order to surpass the US (which has withdrawn from the free trade agreement as one of Trump's first official acts) in the Asia-Pacific region.
China can be remarkably agile when it discovers a political gap and market opening.
Debates would be difficult, but Japan's reservations regarding China's accession to the TPP have decreased since Prime Minister Shinzo Abe's most recent visit to Beijing.
In view of the central strategic challenges in relations with the US, China is likely to be committed in 2019 to general foreign and security policy to reduce conflicts in its relationships with other countries.
In the relations to Japan, there is already a certain normalization.
Recent data from the Japanese Coast Guard indicate a clear reduction in Chinese incursions into the area of the Senkaku-/Diaoyu Islands in the East China Sea.
China will also try to reduce tensions with the Association of Southeast Asian Nations due to the South China Sea by accelerating the negotiation of a "Code of Conduct".
In addition, China should have an easier relationship with India after the bilateral summit in Wuhan in April.
And China could start to moderate its stance towards Taiwan in light of the electoral defeat suffered by the Democratic Progressive Party of Taiwanese President Tsai Ing-wen, who advocates for independence, in the local and regional elections last month.
This would naturally change radically if the US were to continue with further significant arms sales to Taiwan, which is likely.
Incidents at sea with the US in the South China Sea are still occurring and the conflict could intensify if the US were to make its stance on "freedom of navigation" clearer next year.
China is continuing to implement its major project "New Silk Road" across all of Eurasia.
However, the initiative has recently caused less political commotion in China.
Discussions among Chinese officials are already underway to revise certain details, following negative reactions to Sri Lanka's transfer of the Hambantota port to China, and concerns over the long-term financiability of the New Silk Road.
2019 triumphal announcements about the New Silk Road might be heard less frequently.
Furthermore, China will probably solidify and expand its role within the United Nations and existing Bretton Woods institutions rather than highlighting new institutions of international political action.
It will likely continue to appear as a new advocate for the WHO and maintain its stance on global climate change, as agreed upon in the Paris Climate Agreement of 2015.
More cautious representatives of China's foreign policy establishment believe it is better to focus on existing mechanisms of the global rule-based system, especially as the US consistently shows contempt for it.
While China tries to stabilize its relations with the US and reduce tensions in its relations with other countries, its leadership will probably use the year 2019 to form a well-informed judgment about the future of US policy: the consequences of the Mueller investigation for Trump and his government, and whether a new president in 2020 (or earlier) would change the new US strategy in any way.
Although they have already reached the conclusion that America's stance towards China has fundamentally changed, they are still uncertain as to what form this change takes exactly and whether a fundamental change in strategy (as opposed to tactical measures) is indicated.
